      "content": "I see your point about equality, but you seem to be framing the issue as if religious exemptions are inherently a threat to \"fundamental rights.\" Isn't that a bit one-sided? \n\nSome would argue that the right to live according to one's conscience is just as fundamental as the right to non-discrimination. If the state basically tells a religious community, \"you can exist, but only if you agree to ignore your most deeply held values,\" isn't the state effectively becoming a tool of secular coercion? Why is the \"neutral framework\" you're describing considered more legitimate than the protection of religious pluralism?",
